# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: all-rounder
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:all-rounder/1906-english-cricket-season] 1906 was the 17th season of County Championship cricket in England.
[src:all-rounder/1906-english-cricket-season] The title was decided in the final round of matches with Kent County Cricket Club finishing just ahead of Yorkshire.
[src:all-rounder/1906-english-cricket-season] George Hirst completed a unique "double Double" of 2,385 runs and 208 wickets.
[src:all-rounder/1906-english-cricket-season] Tom Hayward broke Bobby Abel’s 1901 record for the most runs scored in a first-class season.
[src:all-rounder/1906-english-cricket-season] The earliest to score 2,000 runs, on 5 July.
[src:all-rounder/1906-english-cricket-season] Two separate hundreds in consecutive matches against Nottinghamshire and Leicestershire.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His bowling was a mainstay of the Australian pace attack of the 1950s and early 1960s, and from the late 1950s he was widely regarded as one of the finest pace bowlers in the world.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson's classical bowling action imparted late swing, allowing him to move the ball to deceive batsmen and he bowled with great control, conceding fewer than two runs per over across his career.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In 2006, writer Geoff Armstrong considered that Davidson was, along with Wasim Akram, one of the two greatest left-arm fast bowlers in history.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was also known for his anticipation in close catching positions and his accurate and strong throwing arm from the outfield; his ability to take improbable close range catches saw him earn the nickname "The Claw".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He was the first player to obtain the distinction of achieving the double of getting ten wickets and scoring 100 runs in the same Test match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The son of Leslie Keith Davidson and Hilda Aileen Clifton, Davidson grew up in Lisarow, New South Wales (NSW) near the city of Gosford on the NSW Central Coast.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He learnt to play cricket on a pitch that he dug out of a hill on his family's rural property.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] By the age of nine, he was playing in the second division of the Gosford grade competition.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Throughout his high school years, he represented Northern High Schools in the state combined public schools' competition where he played against his future Test captain Richie Benaud, who captained City High Schools.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] During his teenage years, Davidson kept fit by working on the family property, chopping wood and carrying farm produce.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson originally bowled left arm unorthodox spin, but when his uncle's team was missing a fast bowler in a country match, Davidson stepped in, remaining a fast bowler permanently.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In 1948–49, he moved to Sydney and joined the Northern Districts grade club.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] A talented rugby league player in his youth, he trained with the Western Districts Football Club in the off season to maintain his fitness.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The Australian Test team was touring South Africa in 1949–50, creating opportunities for young players back home.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This was especially true with respect to fast bowling, as Keith Miller and Ray Lindwall, Australia's two leading pacemen, were from New South Wales and were in South Africa.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In addition, Ernie Toshack, who had been in the Test team since World War II, had broken down.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Amid this environment, Davidson was selected for New South Wales.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] On debut against South Australia, Davidson claimed the wicket of Bob McLean with his second ball and finished with 4/32.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then made 34 with the bat as New South Wales took a 282-run lead, but was unsuccessful in the second innings, taking 0/90 as South Australia held on for a draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He finished the season strongly, with 19 wickets in the last three matches against Queensland, South Australia and Victoria.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This included a haul of 5/28 and 2/37 as he helped New South Wales to a win over their arch-rivals Victoria, who had defeated them earlier in the season.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His debut season ended with 26 wickets at 18.73.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He did not surpass his debut innings with the bat and ended with 110 runs at 15.71.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] These performances earned him selection for the Australian Second XI tour of New Zealand under Bill Brown.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Most of the matches were not first-class, and in the match against Wairarapa he showed his all round skills by taking all ten wickets for 29 and then made an unbeaten 157, helping Australia to a win by an innings and 466 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the only international match against New Zealand for the tour, Davidson made a duck and took 0/36 in the first innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then took 4/24 in the second innings, including the wickets of Bert Sutcliffe and Verdun Scott to help instigate a collapse.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The hosts were 9/76, only eight runs ahead, when time ran out.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ended his maiden tour in Australian colours with nine wickets at 18.22 and 18 runs at 6.00 in three first-class matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With the return of the Test players for the 1950–51 season, Davidson had to perform strongly when given opportunities in order to hold his position.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He started his season productively by taking 7/49 in the first innings of the opening match against Queensland, including the wickets of Test players Ken Archer, Colin McCool and Don Tallon, but he expressed disappointment at his erratic line and length, frequently bowling full tosses and long hops.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] New South Wales won by an innings, and Davidson took four wickets in the return match, but results began to dry up thereafter.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He had the opportunity to show his skills against Test opposition as New South Wales played England ahead of the Tests, but he went wicketless, and was dropped in December after the next match against Western Australia.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson ended the season with 14 wickets at 22.71 and 42 runs at 10.50 from four matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Despite another season of limited opportunities in 1951–52—he played in only four matches—Davidson continued to improve.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He struggled at the outset, taking only four wickets at 41.25 in his four innings, before breaking through against a full-strength Victorian team.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He broke through for his first half-century, scoring 76 before being bowled by Bill Johnston— at the time ranked the No.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then took 4/93 in the second innings, removing Test captain Lindsay Hassett and Australian representatives Ian Johnson and Doug Ring.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then took five wickets in a match against Queensland before bowling his state to victory over Western Australia in his final match for the summer.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took 6/13 to cut down Western Australia for 50 and took 3/36 in the second innings to seal a 250-run win.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson ended the season with 22 wickets at 18.00 and 137 runs at 27.40.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson brought himself to the verge of Test selection in 1952–53; it was the first summer during which he commanded a regular place in a full-strength New South Wales team.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took a total of 6/74 in the second match of the season against Queensland, and then impressed against the touring South African Test team.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took a total of 4/113, including batsmen Jackie McGlew and Russell Endean.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Steady wicket-taking, combined with an all round performance of 66, 40 and 3/89 against Western Australia saw Davidson selected for the Australian XI, which took on South Africa in what was effectively a dress rehearsal for the Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He managed only nine with the bat, but took 5/108 in the only innings of the match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Nevertheless, he was overlooked for Test selection.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took 41 wickets at 26.75 and scored three half-centuries with the bat to total 418 runs at 34.83.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Following these consistent performances, Davidson was selected for the 1953 Ashes tour.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He improved on his career best in consecutive matches against Tasmania before the Australians sailed to England, scoring 87 and 90.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The second effort featured a 167-run partnership with Richie Benaud.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was to be the first of many joint efforts by the pair of bowling all rounders for Australia over the next ten years.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson then took 3/45 with the ball, including the wickets of Miller and leading Australian batsman Neil Harvey.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] After being omitted in the opening tour match against Worcestershire, Davidson made his debut on English soil against Leicestershire.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored 63, featuring in a century partnership with Harvey, before taking 2/23 and 0/35 in an innings victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the next match against Yorkshire, he removed Len Hutton, regarded as the best batsman in the world at the time.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the nine first-class matches leading up to the Tests, Davidson performed steadily without being spectacular.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored two fifties and passed 20 in every completed innings to aggregate 317 runs at 45.28, and took 17 wickets at 22.12, taking more than two wickets in an innings on only one occasion.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] That occasion was against the Marylebone Cricket Club, which was a virtual England Test team, while Australia fielded their strongest possible team.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In what was effectively a dress rehearsal for the Tests, Davidson took 2/17 and 3/49, removing Trevor Bailey, Godfrey Evans, Johnny Wardle, Tom Graveney and leading batsman Denis Compton.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] When the Tests started at Trent Bridge, Davidson was named in the playing XI.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He supported the pace attack of Miller, Lindwall and Johnston in the five Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His debut in the First Test was unremarkable.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] As with most of Australia's batsmen, Davidson struggled against Alec Bedser, who broke the English Test wicket-taking record in the wet conditions, making only four and six.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took 2/22 in the first innings as the match ended in a rain affected draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His first Test wicket was that of Hutton, caught by Benaud, and he added Evans in the latter part of the innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored a hard hitting 76 in the first innings of the Second Test at Lord's to help Australia take control, but a stubborn partnership by Bailey and Willie Watson saw England hang on for a draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson bowled only 24.5 overs for the match, and Wardle was his only wicket.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Rainy weather greeted the players in the Third Test at Old Trafford and more than half the playing time was washed out.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson took 2/60 in the drawn match, removing Reg Simpson and Willie Watson.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia were in a good position at the start of the final day of the Fourth Test at Headingley, with England leading by only 78 runs with five wickets in hand.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However, Bailey (38) and Jim Laker (48) stubbornly resisted with a mixture of time-wasting and dour defence.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson eventually removed both, but there was not enough time remaining to secure an Australian victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His match figures of 3/59 from 50.1 overs were in large part due to the defensive tactics of England.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The fate of The Ashes thus came down to the Fifth Test at The Oval.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson scored 22 and 21 and could not take a wicket as England won by eight wickets to regain the urn for the first time in two decades.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia had blundered by omitting a specialist spinner, mistakenly thinking that the pitch would not spin.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson hit England's spinners out of the attack for a period, but succumbed to the variable bounce of the pitch.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson passed 25 in the Tests only once took two wickets on three occasions.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He finished the series with 182 runs at 22.75 and his sparingly used bowling yielded eight wickets at 26.50.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Despite this, he was Australia's sixth-highest run-scorer and third-leading wicket-taker.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Despite his lack of performance in the Tests, Davidson showed his potential with consistent performance throughout the tour.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He compiled 944 runs at 41.04 during the tour and amassed five half centuries and a century.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored three fifties in the last month of the tour, and after missing his maiden first-class century with 95 against Lancashire, he broke through with 104* against Somerset at County Ground, Taunton.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He also took 50 wickets at 20.96 with the ball.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was steady with the ball, never taking more than three wickets in an innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ranked seventh among the Australians in both run-scoring and wicket-taking.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] During the tour, tensions sometimes arose between the senior players, who were war veterans and drinkers, while the younger players including Davidson tended to abstain from alcohol.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Teammate Ian Craig estimated that bus journeys to matches proceeded at an average speed of 16 km/h because of persistent stoppages outside pubs, something that frustrated the non-drinkers.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the end, the young players had to the majority of the fielding as their older colleagues were often still intoxicated during matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The 1953–54 season was purely domestic, with no Tests scheduled.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson had a modest injury-hit season, scoring 76 runs at 19.00 and taking nine wickets at 32.71 in four matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His best was a 4/50 against Queensland, and 3/89 in a testimonial match for retiring Australian captain Lindsay Hassett; he removed Test teammates Benaud, Ron Archer and Graeme Hole.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In 1954–55 England toured Australia for five Ashes Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson started his season well, scoring 30 and 27 not out and taking a total of 5/104 as New South Wales drew with England.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His victims included leading batsmen Colin Cowdrey and Bill Edrich.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However, Davidson succumbed to injury and missed Australia's only win of the series in the First Test, and upon his return in the Second Test, managed match figures of 2/86 and did not pass twenty in either innings as England levelled the series.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He was dropped for the Third Test, but continued to perform strongly in domestic matches, including a sequence of 19 wickets in three matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This included 4/45 including the wickets of Compton, Bailey and Graveney in a tour match against England, and a match-winning performance against arch-rivals Victoria that sealed a second successive Shield triumph with a resounding nine-wicket win in two days.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He tore through the Victorians with 5/36 and 4/50, removing Harvey and Test all rounder Sam Loxton twice.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was his best match bowling figures in his career to date.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was recalled for the Fourth Test, but managed only a wicket as England sealed the series 4–1.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However, he then took a total of 6/68 as New South Wales defeated England; it was only the second time the tourists had lost for the summer.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was retained for the final Test, his first on his home ground in Sydney, but was wicketless in a rain-affected draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His Test series had been poor, with 71 runs at 14.20 and only three wickets at 73.33 as England retained the Ashes 3–1.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson had not tasted victory in any of his eight Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His poor Test form contrasted to his performances against England in tour matches; he took 15 wicket at 15.13 in three matches outside the Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His overall bowling performance was strong, with 34 wickets at 23.18, although his batting was ineffective, with only 213 runs at 15.21 and a top-score of 30.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was selected for the 1954–55 tour of the West Indies, where he injured his right ankle in a tour match against Jamaica and missed the First Test against the West Indies.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Upon his recovery, he could not break into the XI and did not play in any of the Tests, which Australia won 3–0.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored 70 runs at 35.00 and took four wickets at 51.75 in three first-class outings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] After his injury-hit Caribbean sojourn, Davidson had the 1955–56 season, which was purely domestic, to force his way back into the national team for the 1956 tour of England.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Johnston had also retired, leaving an extra vacancy for a pace bowler.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He started strongly with match figures of 7/87 in a drawn match against Queensland in Brisbane.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The hosts managed to hang on with three wickets in hand, after Davidson's captain had held up play and wasted 20 minutes for the running of the Melbourne Cup.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He performed steadily for the next six matches, not taking more than two wickets in any innings, before playing a prominent role in the final match of the Sheffield Shield season against Victoria.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was then 100th anniversary of matches between the old rivals.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson took 6/99 in the first innings, including Harvey for 128, before adding 2/61 in the second.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It helped prevent a defeat on the anniversary and sealed New South Wales' hat-trick of Shield titles.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was selected for the England tour and then took 12 wickets and scored his only half-century of the season as the Australians warmed up before sailing abroad.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ended the Australian season with 350 runs at 31.81 and 36 wickets at 25.19.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson had an interrupted lead-in to the Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He injured himself while batting in his sixth match, against the MCC, and was unable to take any further part in the match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He was out of action for two weeks but recovered in time for the First Test at Trent Bridge.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He had scored 46 runs at 11.50 and took 13 wickets at 20.92 during his preparation.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the First Test of the series at Nottingham, Davidson removed Cowdrey before his ankle slipped in a footmark during the first innings and a bone was chipped.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He was carried off with figures of 1/22 and his ankle plastered.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The injury was such that he was unable to bat even with the assistance of a runner and was absent.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] By the time of Davidson's return, England had retained the Ashes 2–1 after annihilating Australia by an innings in consecutive Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Prior to this, Australia had not lost by an innings since 1938, let alone twice in a row.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The Surrey finger spin pairing of Jim Laker and Tony Lock had led the decimation, taking 38 of the 40 wickets of dry dusty wickets doctored for their use.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In Australia's match against Surrey before the Tests, the pair had taken 19 wickets as the tourists lost to a county side for the first time since 1912.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] As a result of the finger spinners' success, Australian captain Ian Johnson tried to convert Davidson into a left arm orthodox spinner.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson returned as Australia faced a fourth meeting with Laker and Lock, in a match against Surrey immediately after the two consecutive Test maulings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] On a sticky wicket that played into the hands of the Surrey spinners, Australia were skittled for 143.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Only Davidson, who took the attack to the pair, made 44 not out.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] One six that he lofted from Laker almost reached the iconic gasometer outside The Oval.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The match was drawn, and Davidson took 2/50 including Eric Bedser and Laker in his new role as a slow bowler.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was able to force his way back into the team for the Fifth Test at The Oval.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored eight and took a total of 1/34 in another rain-marred draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Johnson persisted in using Davidson as a spinner, but it was not effective.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In eight matches, the ploy yielded only 12 wickets at 24.25.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Johnson was criticised for this novel strategy; cricket writer Ray Robinson said "I have not met one good cricketer or cricket judge who is not mystified by them [Johnson's tactics]".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson felt that Johnson tried to rely too heavily on the senior players and should have placed more responsibility on the likes of Richie Benaud, Ron Archer and himself.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Overall Davidson scored 270 runs at 27.00 with two fifties and took 26 wickets at 22.50 in England.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] On the return leg to Australia, the team stopped on the Indian subcontinent.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson's 37 in the inaugural one-off Test against Pakistan was his first score beyond 25 in nine Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He was bowled sparingly with a total of 2/15 from 15 overs as Australia lost by nine wickets.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] A muscle problem stopped Davidson from playing against India in the First Test in Madras, which Australia won by an innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He played only in the Second Test, with pacemen Miller and Ron Archer injured and unavailable.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It got worse for Australia as Davidson and fellow paceman Pat Crawford were hampered by stomach bugs and a hip strains respectively.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson scored 16 and took match figures of 1/42; Australia were unable to finish off the Indians with their depleted attack and the match ended in a draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was left out of the Third Test win, so his overseas tour had ended without a Test victory, and only 64 runs at 16.00 and his underused bowling yielded five wickets at 22.60.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In total, he had played twelve Tests, none of them resulting in an Australian victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His individual performances were also unimpressive despite being successful at first-class level, producing only 317 runs at 18.64 and 16 wickets at 34.06.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was to be another year before Davidson tasted victory at the highest level.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With captain Johnson and vice captain Miller, the main spinner and one of the two leading fast bowlers retiring upon their return from the subcontinent, Australia moved into uncharted territory and needed younger bowlers to step up following three successive series losses to England.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The 1956–57 Australian season was purely domestic and a chance for the players to stake their claims to be part of Australia's future.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson scored 374 runs at 34.00 including three fifties and took 30 wicket at 27.50 from eight matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His most effective effort was a 5/65 in the second innings of the match between Harvey's XI and Lindwall's XI.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson's effort helped set up a seven-wicket triumph for Harvey's men.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Over the winter, with Test vacancies beckoning, Davidson and Benaud became training partners and decided to bowl for three hours continuously on a daily basis through the winter off season.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With Ray Lindwall dropped, Davidson and Benaud became Australia's leading paceman and spinner when the team for the 1957–58 tour of South Africa was announced.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was a heavy burden on Davidson, who had only taken two Test wickets in an innings four times, and three wickets in a Test match on one occasion.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The team was to be led by Ian Craig, who had played only six Tests, and at the age of just 22 years, he was the youngest ever Test captain from any country.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson started the tour well, when Australia arrived in Rhodesia (now Zimbabwe) to play two tour matches against the Rhodesia.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He made an unbeaten 100 and took a total of 3/67 in the first match in Salisbury, before scoring 19 and taking 5/36 and 2/22 in the second in Bulawayo.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The Australians crossed the border into South Africa and Davidson scored 100 and took a total of 4/62 against Transvaal as Craig's men started with a nine-wicket win.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The next match was against a South African XI, and was effectively a dress rehearsal for the Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson scored 34 and took a total of 7/103 as the Australians crushed the hosts by an innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He rounded off his Test preparation with match figures of 6/35 against Border and a 76 against Western Province.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Despite the highly productive lead-up, Davidson faltered in his first outing as Australia's Test spearhead.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He conceded 1/115 in only 32 overs in the first innings as South Africa reached 9/470 in the First Test in Johannesburg.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With Australia 102 behind on the first innings, Davidson's tour nearly ended.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Unable to cope with the 10 pm curfew imposed by team manager Jack Norton, Davidson and roommate Les Favell absconded and went sightseeing.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] By the time they had returned, Norton had confiscated their keys and left them a note asking them to report.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The pair then went to sleep at the home of some supporters who had hosted the team for dinner the previous day.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The next day, Davidson faced dismissal from the team, but he overcame the turmoil to take 6/34, his first five wicket haul.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This included a seven-over spell before lunch that yielded three wickets and reduced South Africa to 4/19, before the match ended in a draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson, Favell and their hosts all told Norton that the pair of cricketers had stayed the entire night at the home.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The duo were not sent home the curfew was repealed.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The Second Test in Cape Town saw an Australian victory, the first in Davidson's 14 Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took 2/31 and 2/18 as South Africa lost by an innings after being forced to follow on.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was during this match that Davidson earned his famous reputation for injury complaints, something that became a constant source of humour; he spent so much time on the massage table that his teammates attached a plaque that read "The AK Davidson Autograph Treatment Table".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Benaud reported that Davidson persistently complained to captain Craig about an injury before delivering the next ball with high pace and swing.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then scored 123 against Natal before the Third Test in Durban, where he took 2/62 in a drawn match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the Fourth Test in Johannesburg, Davidson made 62, his first Test half century in over four years, and took a total of 3/83 in a ten-wicket victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then took match figures of 7/55 against Griqualand West and recorded his best first-class score of 129 in a match against Western Province in Cape Town.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then took 5/38 to help seal another innings win.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the Fifth Test at Port Elizabeth, Davidson took 4/44 and then 5/38 in the second innings as he and Benaud took all ten wickets and South Africa were skittled for 144.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia won by eight wickets and took the series 3–0.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was his best Test match haul to date.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored 127 runs at 21.17 and took 25 wickets at 17.0 in the Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He had success against Russell Endean and John Waite, dismissing both twice.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Although he was unable to score heavily in the Tests, Davidson scored four of his nine first class centuries during the tour.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In all, he had taken 72 wickets at 15.13 and scored 813 runs at 54.20 for the entire tour.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] From this tour onwards, in 32 Tests, he was to take 170 wickets at 19.26 and score 1011 runs at 27.32 in the remainder of his career.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The 1958–59 English tour of Australia saw Davidson lead the attack for the first time in Australia.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was Australia's first series on home soil since the last English visit four years earlier and came on the back of three successive Ashes series losses.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson started well with match figures of 5/66 as Australia took the First Test in Brisbane by eight wickets.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the Second Test in Melbourne, Davidson took 6/64 in the first innings to help bowl out the tourists for 259 and put Australia in control.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This included an opening spell in which he removed the three top order English batsmen Peter Richardson, Watson and Tom Graveney without conceding a run.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He had Richardson caught behind from the first ball of his second over, before yorking Watson with the fourth ball for duck and trapping Graveney leg before wicket from the next delivery with an inswinger.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This brought England captain Peter May to the crease, but Davidson'a hat-trick ball was off target and no shot was offered.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He later returned to remove Colin Cowdrey, Brian Statham and Peter Loader.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the second innings, he bowled unchanged with Ian Meckiff, taking 3/41, and taking two reflex catches in the leg trap from Meckiff, as England were cut down for 87 and Australia took an eight-wicket win and a 2–0 lead.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson's least penetrative match was the Third Test in Sydney, taking a match total of 2/84.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It coincided with Australia's only non-victory of the series.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson scored 71 as the match ended in a draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took three and five wickets in the final two Tests, both of which Australia won.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson ended the series with 24 wickets at 19.00.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With the bat, Davidson had his most productive Test series yet, scoring 180 runs at 36.00.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia had defeated Peter May's team, who were heavily favoured, with ease.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] According to cricket writer Gideon Haigh, "Davidson had the ball on a string".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson added a century in a state match against South Australia and for the entire first-class season, he totalled 431 runs at 33.15 and 47 wickets at 18.04.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The 1959–60 season saw Davidson confronted with an arduous eight Test tour of the Indian subcontinent, with three and five Tests against Pakistan and India respectively.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Flat and dry pitches unconducive to fast bowling combined with oppressive heat confronted the players.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] On the last tour, many of the Australians had fallen ill with food positioning, and Davidson had asked Donald Bradman, the Australian Chairman of Selectors if opting out of the tour was permitted.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was consistent throughout the Pakistan series, taking four wickets in each of the three Tests, to end with 12 wickets at 24.83.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He also batted solidly, with 47 and 39* in the latter two Tests to end with 90 runs at 45.00.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His contributions helped Australia to a 2–0 series result; it was the first time Pakistan had lost a Test on home soil and the pair of victories were its last in Pakistan for 39 years.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He had particular success against Imtiaz Ahmed, removing him four times.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the First Test against India in Delhi, Davidson took 3/22 in the first innings, removing both openers Pankaj Roy and Nari Contractor, and captain Polly Umrigar to help Australia seize the initiative and bowl out the hosts for 135.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then contributed four catches in the second as Australia took a 1–0 series lead with an innings victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The Second Test in Kanpur saw Davidson return his career best innings and match bowling figures.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] On a dry pitch and in searing temperatures unfavourable for fast bowling, he took 5/31 in the first innings as India were all out for 152.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then scored 41 as Australia replied with 219.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In heat above 38 degrees Celsius, he bowled unchanged for the entire day to take 7/93 from 57.3 overs in the second innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] During the match, Davidson lost around 11 kg in weight.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] According to the Australians, it was the "harshest cricket environment" that they had encountered.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson said that he felt like a "bloody zombie".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia were left a target of 225 for victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson fell for eight as part of a Jasu Patel-inspired collapse.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Patel took 14/124 and Australia were out for 105.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This resulted in Australia's first loss in the fifteen Tests since Davidson began leading the attack, and their first at the hands of their hosts.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson took 4/62 in the first innings of the Third Test in Delhi as Australia took a 98-run first innings lead, but he was unable to add to his tally in the second innings as the hosts' batsmen held on for a draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then took taking match figures of 5/69 and 5/113 in the last two matches as Australia managed to win the Fourth Test to take a hard-fought 2–1 series victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson had led the way with 29 wickets at 14.86 in a country regarded as a graveyard for fast bowling—in this era, the home team's attack was dominated by spinners.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In six Tests in India, Davidson had taken 30 wickets at an average of 15.77.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was at his all round peak during the 1960–61 series against West Indies.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] After taking eight wickets in the two opening matches of the season against Queensland, Davidson gave an indication of what was in store in the Tests when New South Wales played Frank Worrell's tourists.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He struck 88 as the hosts amassed 6/429 declared and then took three top-order wickets, removing Cammie Smith, Rohan Kanhai and Gary Sobers, holder of the Test world record of 365.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ended with 4/26 as the West Indies fell for 111 and lost by an innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then completed his Test preparation with 122 not out against Victoria.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the First Test against the West Indies cricket team in Brisbane, Davidson showed his all round skills as well as stamina in becoming the first player to take ten wickets and accumulate more than a hundred runs in a match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] On the eve of the match, Davidson broke the little finger on his bowling hand during catching practice and was unable to move it.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However, he decided to play after Bradman gave a motivational speech to the team ahead of the match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] On the first two days, he bowled thirty (eight ball) overs to take 5/135 in the first innings as the West Indies reached 453.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He did much of the heavy lifting in removing four of the West Indies' batsmen, Conrad Hunte, Smith, Kanhai and Worrell.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia took a small lead of 52 after reaching 505, with Davidson contributing 44.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the second innings, Davidson was left with a heavier workload after his new ball partner Meckiff broke down after four overs.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took 6/87 from 24.6 overs as the West Indies were restricted to 284. he was again responsible for cutting down the leading batsmen, removing Smith, Kanhai, Sobers and Worrell.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This left Australia 233 runs to win with 312 minutes available on the last day.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Former Australian Test batsman and journalist Jack Fingleton commented that "One sensed that the West Indies realised they were facing defeat".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Although time was plentiful, the pitch had begun to deteriorate and Australia look defeated after they had fallen to 5/57, prompting Davidson to join local batsman Ken Mackay at the crease.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] They took the score to 92 when Mackay fell and Australia's chances of winning looked remote as Davidson and Benaud reached tea at 6/109 with 124 runs still required with only the tailenders were to follow.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Despite this, Benaud told chairman of selectors Don Bradman that he would still be going for an improbable victory in accordance with his policy of aggressive strategy.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With an attacking partnership, the pair took Australia to within sight of the target.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson hooked leading paceman Wes Hall repeatedly and Benaud attacked the spinners when Worrell took Hall off.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Both men were noted for their hitting ability and viewed attack as their most effective chance of survival.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson hit four fours from the leg spin of Sonny Ramadhin, and the deficit dwindled to 60 with one hour remaining and 27 with 30 minutes to go.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The pair took 17 runs from the next two overs, and regular boundaries and quickly run singles took Australia into what looked like a victorious position.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] They took the score to 226 with a seventh wicket partnership of 134.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Only seven runs were required with four wickets in hand as time was running short.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Benaud hit a ball into the covers and the pair attempted a quick single, but a direct hit from Joe Solomon saw Davidson run out for his highest Test score of 80.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson reflected "I was as dirty as anyone ever has been".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia needed six runs from the final over with three wickets in hand but Benaud was caught and the last two players fell to run outs while attempting the winning run.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The match was the first tie in Test cricket, and Davidson had achieved his unprecedented feat despite carrying a broken finger into the match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Bradman joked that he should break his finger before every match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] During that same tied test match, he set a new record for becoming the first player to complete a double of 100 runs and 11 wickets in a same test match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The record was later achieved by only three other men in test cricket history including Ian Botham, Imran Khan and Shakib Al Hasan.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] After this marathon effort, Davidson scored 81 as New South Wales defeated the tourists by an innings for the second time in the space of the month.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He was only asked to bowl five overs after his efforts in Brisbane.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson returned to a full workload as he helped Australia take a 1–0 series lead in the Second Test in Melbourne.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He scored 35 in the first innings of 348, before taking 6/53 in the West Indies' reply of 181.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He removed Joe Solomon, before removing the established batsmen Seymour Nurse and Kanhai to trigger a collapse.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This allowed Benaud to enforce the follow on.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson took a further 2/51 in the second innings to set up a seven wicket victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The teams moved to Sydney for the next Test, where Davidson's unhappy experiences on his home ground continued.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The West Indies batted first and made 339; Davidson took 5/80, including Smith, Kanhai and Sobers.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson made 16 as Australia replied with 202 and were in trouble when Meckiff was forced off the field early in the tourists' second innings with injury.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson lifted and removed Hunte, Kanhai and Sobers for single figures with the new ball.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However, he too was forced off with a hamstring tear.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With Australia two men down, the West Indies recovered to 326 and set the hosts 464 for victory, which would have required a world record fourth innings score.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson managed only one as Australia lost by 222 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He had not had a Test win in Sydney in three attempts, the only Australian ground where he had not played in a victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] After missing the Fourth Test because of a month on the sidelines to recuperate from the hamstring tear, he returned for the Fifth Test with the series level at 1–1.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took match figures of 6/173, including five wickets with late swing in the second innings to help Australia secure the victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson scored 28 and 12 as Benaud's men stumbled in the run-chase before scraping home by two wickets.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In three and a half Tests, he accumulated 212 runs at 30.28 and totalled 33 wickets against the Caribbean visitors at a cost of 18.55, when the next best average of any bowler was 33.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was regarded as the main factor in Australia's 2–1 series win.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ended the first-class season with 551 runs at 55.10 and 45 wickets at 20.62.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] These efforts led him to retain the number 1 ranking in ICC Test Bowlers ranking for 1961 (which he obtained in the previous year).
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The 1961 tour of England was Davidson's overseas farewell, and he had not been prolific on his two previous visits, never managing to take more than four wickets in an innings and totaling only 76 in 40 first-class matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He broke through for his first five-wicket haul on English soil in his fifth match against Glamorgan, taking 5/63 in the first innings and scoring an unbeaten 68.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He added 90 in the next match against Gloucestershire before facing the MCC at Lord's in the traditional dress rehearsal for the Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took 6/46 and 3/58 as Australia took victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] His wickets included leading Test batsmen Cowdrey and Ken Barrington.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson headed into the Tests with 257 runs at 42.83 and 26 wickets at 22.35 from eight matches.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Despite this form, his Test campaign started poorly with an ineffective 1/130 in the drawn First Test at Edgbaston.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then broke down with a back injury in a match against Kent and looked unlikely to play.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] With Benaud already sidelined with a shoulder injury, Australia looked severely weakened without their two main bowlers.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Despite again complaining about frailties of his body, Davidson vowed to play and produce a special performance for friend and stand-in captain Neil Harvey in the Second Test at Lord's.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson took copious amounts of capsulin, and he took his position in what was known as the "Battle of the Ridge" due to the presence of a ridge on the surface that yielded erratic bounce.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He exploited this in the first innings, beating Raman Subba Row three times in the first over and striking Geoff Pullar in the shoulder.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then bowled Pullar and struck Ted Dexter twice in the chest.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Dexter then hit a ball to short leg but was dropped.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson then removed Peter May and Barrington before ending with 5/42 as Australia dismissed the hosts for 206 to seize the initiative.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson credited the performance to the capsulin, which flowed into his lower body and in his own words, put his "backside on fire".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia took a first innings lead of 134 and Davidson removed Subba Row and Barrington with the new ball in the second innings to end with 2/50 and help set up a five wicket victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was at the crease when the winning runs were scored, albeit at the non-striker's end.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was the first time Davidson had tasted Test victory on English soil in three tours.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He then took 5/63 in the first innings of the Third Test at Headingley, removing Subba Row, May, Barrington and Ted Dexter at the top of the order, but Australia struggled with the bat and England lost only two wickets in reaching 62 in the second innings to level the series.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson took one of those wickets, removing Subba Row.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson played a large role in the Fourth Test Old Trafford.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Victory would give Australia an unassailable 2–1 series lead and retention of the Ashes.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] A loss would mean that Australia would need to win the Fifth and final Test to prevent England from reclaiming them.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia started poorly, and Davidson made a duck as the tourists were dismissed for 190.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson then took 3/67, removing Pullar, May and Subba Row as England took a sizeable 177-run lead.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This appeared to be a match-winning lead after Australia had lost three wickets in quick succession to David Allen, leaving them at 9/334 with only a 157 run lead.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Last man Graham McKenzie came to the crease to join Davidson, who had been in poor form with the bat, having failed to pass 22 in the past five matches in six weeks.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson said that "I was shaking like I had Parkinson's".
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] May brought on the part-time spin of Brian Close and 15 runs came in two overs, helping Davidson to feel more at ease.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] At the time, Allen had bowled 25 maidens in 37 overs.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson responded to the situation by hitting Allen out of the attack.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In Allen's 10th over for the day, Davidson took 20 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He lofted an off drive over the boundary for six, and drove through the covers for four from both the front and back foot.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson then hit the bowler out of the stadium onto the adjacent railway lines.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Fred Trueman came on and struck Davidson on the foot with a yorker.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson responded with a three and a cut for four that brought up Australia's 400.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ended with a hard-hitting 77 not out, after a final wicket partnership of 98 in 102 minutes.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This extended Australia's lead to 256 on the last day and gave them hope of stopping England from winning the match.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] England looked to be heading towards victory with seven wickets in hand and less than 100 runs required, but a Benaud-inspired collapse saw Australia home by 54 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson knocked Brian Statham's off stump out of the ground to end the match and ended with 2/50.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] It was Australia's first victory at Old Trafford since 1902 and sealed the series.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ended his final Test series on foreign soil with combined figures of 4/150 in the Fifth Test at The Oval, which was drawn.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson finished the series with 23 wickets at 24.87 and 151 runs at 30.20.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He was again Australia's leading bowler on tour.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson bade farewell to the English first-class scene with a match-winning display with both bat and ball against AER Gilligan's XI.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He took 3/45 and scored 65 and 60, helping Australia to scrape home by three wickets.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was in strong all round form in the 1961–62 Australian season, which was a purely domestic one.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Against Victoria in Sydney, he scored 106 in a hard hitting innings with the tail.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He made 58 of the 59 runs added in a last wicket partnership with Doug Ford, the other being a leg bye.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The partnership lasted only 44 balls and Davidson managed to farm the strike and face 41 of these.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The effort helped to set up a ten-wicket win.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The following week against Western Australia in Perth, he made 108 after New South Wales had slumped to 6/38 to help the visitors recover to 218.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] New South Wales struggled in their second innings and Western Australia needed only 175 for victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However, Davidson took his career best innings bowling figures of 7/31 to bowl out the hosts for 106 and seize a victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In both matches against Queensland, Davidson took four quick wickets in the second innings to secure narrow victories after bold declarations.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] New South Wales won the Shield in that season with 64 of a maximum possible 80 points, playing aggressive cricket under Benaud.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was a key factor in the dominance, scoring 521 runs at 40.07 and taking 42 wickets at 13.62.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] At the start of the season, Davidson announced that the 1962–63 Ashes series against England was to be his last in the international arena, citing family and business reasons for his retirement.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He started the season with half-centuries in the three consecutive innings ahead of the Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The third of these was in a state match that resulted in an innings victory over England.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However, he started the Tests slowly, failing to take a wicket in the first innings of the First Test at Brisbane before securing 3/43 in the second as the match was drawn.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He removed Barrington, Pullar and David Sheppard.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] However he returned to form with 96 and 4/80 against South Australia, and then added a milestone to his first-class career with a hat-trick against Western Australia in Perth.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Having taken a wicket with the first ball of the innings, Davidson proceeded to bowl both Barry Shepherd and John Parker before Russell Waugh was caught by Norm O'Neill in the first innings.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He ended with 5/40 and took 2/32 in the second innings as the visitors completed an innings victory.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the Second Test at Melbourne, Davidson made 40 in Australia's first innings of 316. and then captured 6/75 to restrict England's lead to 15.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia then 248 with Davidson contributing 17, but he went wicketless in the second innings as England successfully reached their target with seven wickets in hand to take a 1–0 series lead.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This left Australia with a victory target of only 65, which was reached just before the beginning of a heavy thunderstorm that would have caused the remainder of the match to be abandoned, thus saving England from defeat.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson struck 46 runs in the first innings of the Fourth Test in Adelaide, then tore his hamstring muscle after bowling only 3.4 overs.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Australia, with a bowler short, was unable to force a win without him.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The Fifth Test was on his home ground at Sydney with the series locked 1–1.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] He captured 3/43 and 3/80, taking a wicket with his final ball in Test cricket when Alan Smith was caught at slip by Bob Simpson.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This left Australia with a target of 241 in 60 overs, but there was to be no fairytale finish as the match ended in a draw.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] The Ashes series was the only one of seven series that Australia failed to win since Davidson became the team's frontline strike bowler in 1957–58.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Of the 33 Tests in this period, Australia won 16, lost four, drew 12 and tied one.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson missed one of the drawn games through injury and broke down mid-match in another two.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the five years that he and Benaud led Australia's bowling attack, the pair totalled 333 wickets; Davidson 170 at 19.25 and Benaud 163 at 25, and were a major part in Australia's return to the forefront of world cricket.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] This came after the first four years of Davidson's career saw Australia win none and lose seven matches out of twelve.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Often bowling in tandem, Davidson's accuracy also forced opposition batsmen to attack Benaud, leading them to perish from the pressure to raise the run rate.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the four years after Davidson retired, Australia struggled without his wicket-taking ability.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Only one of the six series was won and two were lost; in all Australia managed six wins and eight losses in 30 Tests.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] Davidson was at his best when Australia was on her knees; In the four Test losses during the last five years of his career, he took 32 wickets at an average of just 13.9 including a ten wicket haul.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p01] In the Tied Test, he took eleven wickets, the other ten wicket haul in his Test career.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] In Sydney Grade Cricket, he scored 4,302 runs at 37.08 and took 348 wickets at 13.69.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He later served as a selector for the Australian team from 1979 to 1984, and after serving as a vice president for three years, in 1970 became president of the New South Wales Cricket Association.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] At the age of 41, he was the youngest person to have held the post.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson was one of the trustees of the SCG from 1978 to 1998, during which time floodlights were installed at the ground.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson held positions on the board of directors of a variety of organisations, sporting, medical, philanthropic and corporate.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He was the chairman of Freshfood Australia Holdings, and was the president of Surf Life Saving Australia from 1984 to 2002.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He served as a member of the New South Wales Sport Advisory Council from 1988 to 2008, and the national equivalent from 1977 to 1981, and served as a director of the ANZAC Health and Research Foundation from 1994 to 2003.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He held positions with the Australian Red Cross and Legacy Australia.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson also worked as a teller for the Commonwealth Bank from 1947 to 1974.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson also served as the chairman of the Rothmans National Sports Foundation for six years.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He served on the New South Wales Olympic Council from 1980 to 1996.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He published his autobiography *Fifteen Paces* in 1963, a reference to the length of his bowling run.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] A suburban cricket and Australian rules football ground in Alexandria, in Sydney's inner-west, is named after Davidson.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] There is also a suburban cricket and soccer oval in Wyoming, New South Wales, on the Central Coast that is named after Davidson, as well as a cricket and rugby field located in Homebush.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] In 2013 Davidson appeared in a television commercial for his former employer, the Commonwealth Bank.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson appears as an aged dog walker watching a young boy practise his bowling.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson married Betty Patricia McKinley in 1952.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Their sons were born in 1953 and 1955 while he was on tour in England and the West Indies respectively.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He was named as the New South Wales Father of the Year in 1982.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson died in Sydney on 30 October 2021, aged 92.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] Davidson was named as one of the five Wisden Cricketers of the Year in 1962.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He was made a Member of the order of the British Empire (MBE) in 1964 and a Member of the Order of Australia (AM) in 1987.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He was inducted into the Sport Australia Hall of Fame in 1988, the Australian Cricket Hall of Fame in 2004, and the ICC Hall of Fame in 2011.
[src:all-rounder/alan-davidson-cricketer-born-1929-p02] He received an Australian Sports Medal in 2000.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] Relf was an all-rounder who batted in the middle order and bowled off-breaks at medium pace with great accuracy.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] Gilbert Jessop described him as “the master of the swerve”.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] He played Minor Counties cricket for Norfolk, a coaching engagement with the Earl of Wilton at Houghton Hall gaining him a residential qualification.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] At the age of 25, he returned to Sussex to play for the county of his birth, initially enjoying mixed success.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] At first he played as a batsman who bowled a bit, his bowling developed in 1903 to the point where he was picked for the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) tour to Australia under Plum Warner.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] He played in two Tests, helping Tip Foster add 115 for the ninth wicket in his first match at Sydney.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] In the first Test at Johannesburg in 1905–06, he bowled the ball, allegedly down the leg-side, that enabled South Africa to record the first-ever victory over England.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] Warner, again his captain, was reported to have sighed: "Oh, Albert.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] In county cricket, Relf was prolific, achieving the "double" of 1000 runs and 100 wickets eight times, with a best in 1913 of 1846 runs and 141 wickets.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] He was a *Wisden* Cricketer of the Year in 1914, where it was said of his batting style: "No one seeing him for the first time would suppose him capable of getting his hundreds in high-class company," *Wisden* said.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] "He has a way of letting the ball hit the bat that is certainly not impressive to the eye.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] Writing in the 1940s, Dan Reese said, "He was the best cricket coach we have had in New Zealand, being most thorough in his methods and making his young players work at the game." Relf also played eight first-class matches for Auckland, scoring 633 runs at 52.75 and taking 53 wickets at 11.79.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] Auckland were unbeaten in the Plunket Shield during Relf's tenure.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] Relf played on after the First World War, scoring 153 against Leicestershire at Horsham in his final season, 1921.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] He was awarded a benefit game (v Leicestershire) in 1921.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] The funds raised included the generous donation of 100 guineas by his former captain, KL Ranjitsinhji.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] By this time, Relf's appearances were limited as he had succeeded his father as cricket coach at Wellington College, and he played later for Berkshire in the Minor Counties.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] Relf shot himself at Wellington, apparently depressed by the illness of his wife.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] He left the considerable estate for the time of £20,880.
[src:all-rounder/albert-relf] His two younger brothers, Robert and Ernest, also played first-class cricket.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] After emerging as an all-rounder following the First World War, Kennedy played five Test matches for England on the Marylebone Cricket Club's 1922–23 tour of South Africa.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He was chosen as one of five *Wisden* Cricketers of the Year for 1934.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 677 first-class matches, he took 2,874 wickets, including 225 five wicket hauls.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His career total is the seventh highest in first-class cricket, with his 2,549 wickets for Hampshire second only to Derek Shackleton's 2,669.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] As a batsman, he scored 16,586 runs making ten centuries.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Having started out as a tailend batsman, Kennedy's batting improved as his career progressed that by the early 1920s, he was entrusted with opening the batting.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Following his retirement, Kennedy coached cricket at Cheltenham College and later in South Africa from 1947 to 1954.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He died on 15 November 1959, having been unwell for several months.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Alexander Stuart Kennedy was born in Edinburgh on 24 January 1891.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His family left Scotland when he was a young boy, moving south to England where they settled in Southampton.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He took an interest in cricket as a child and would bowl in the nets at the County Ground in Southampton.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Upon leaving school at the age of 14, he joined the groundstaff at Hampshire alongside Alex Bowell, George Brown, Walter Livsey, Phil Mead, and Jack Newman; together, they formed the first major intake of professional cricketers at Hampshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Over the following two years, Kennedy would play country house cricket in and around Southampton, most notably for the Brockenhurst Park Estate in the New Forest.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] During this time, he would be coached by Charlie Llewellyn, learning the bowling skills of flight and length by aiming to pitch the ball on a piece of paper in the nets.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] At the age of 16, Kennedy made his debut in first-class cricket for Hampshire as a right-arm medium pace bowler against Leicestershire at Aylestone Road in the 1907 County Championship, taking figures of 4 wickets for 33 rusn in Leicestershire's first innings.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He made a second appearance that season, against Warwickshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He played four first-class matches in the 1908 season, claiming his maiden five wicket haul (6 for 41) against the touring Gentlemen of Philadelphia.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy gained a regular place in the Hampshire the following season, making 15 appearances and establishing his bowling partnership with Jack Newman, which was to span two decades and form the backbone of the Hampshire attack.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He took 31 wickets in 1909, averaging 21.96 runs per wicket.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He made 20 appearances in 1910, taking 31 wickets for the second successive season.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 1911, he bowled nearly twice as many overs as he had in 1910, taking 51 wickets at a bowling average of 30.70 from 23 matches.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He claimed five or more wickets in an innings on five occasions.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] It was during this season that his credentials as an all-rounder began to come to the fore, with Kennedy scoring his first half-century (62 runs) and scoring 545 runs at a batting average of 18.46.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] The following season, Kennedy took a hundred wickets in a season for the first time.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 28 appearances, he took 139 wickets, averaging 17.60; he took five wickets or more in an innings on 15 occasions and ten wickets in a match on four.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His best innings figures during the season of 7 for 29 came against Surrey in bowler friendly conditions at Bournemouth, whilst against the touring Australians he took 11 wickets in the match, having taken 6 for 90 in their first innings and 5 for 91 in their second.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He ended the season as the third leading wicket-taker in the 1912 County Championship, behind Colin Blythe, and George Dennett.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] At the start of the 1913 season, Kennedy was taken ill with appendicitis, which required an operation.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] It was expected that this would keep out of the team until July, however, he had returned to the team by June.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Despite missing the early part of the season, Kennedy still managed to take 82 wickets, averaging 23.21 from 20 appearances.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He had a prolific season in 1914, which was truncated in August by the outbreak of the First World War, taking 162 wickets at an average of 20.01 from 31 appearances; he took five or more wickets in an innings ten times.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He ended the season as the second leading wicket-taker in the County Championship, behind Blythe.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Against Somerset, he and Arthur Jaques bowled unchanged in the match to dismiss Somerset for scores of 83 and 38.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In July, he made his first appearance for the Players in the Gentlemen versus Players fixture.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] With the outbreak of war, the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) President Francis Lacey confirmed the cessation of cricket during the war, and first-class cricket in England remained suspended until 1919.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy enlisted in the war with the 5th Battalion, Hampshire Regiment, alongside peers from Hampshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His first match following the cessation of hostilities was for L.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Robinson's personal team against the Australian Imperial Forces in May 1919, with Kennedy subsequently making two appearances for the MCC at Lord's against Yorkshire and the Australian Imperial Forces.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In the 1919 County Championship he led Hampshire's bowling aggregates with 80 wickets, averaging 25.70, single-handedly leading the Hampshire attack in the absence of Newman, who spent 1919 waiting to be demobilised from the army.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Against Surrey at The Oval in June, he took 7 for 47, helping to inflict one of only three home defeats for Surrey between the end of the war and 1927.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 25 first-class matches in 1919, he scored 452 runs and made three half-centuries.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In addition to his appearances for Hampshire and the MCC, he played three times for the Players in the Players versus Gentlemen fixtures of 1919, and appeared for The Rest at The Oval in the season ending Champion County fixture against Yorkshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] During the winter that followed the 1919 season, Kennedy travelled to British India, where he coached Prince Yashwant Rao Holkar at Indore.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In the 1920 season, Kennedy took 160 wickets from 29 appearances, averaging 18.30; he took five wickets or more in an innings on 16 occasions and ten or more in a match on four.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] For Hampshire in the 1920 County Championship, he took 164 wickets and was the Championship's joint-leading wicket-taker alongside Frank Woolley.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His best innings figures that season, 9 for 33, came in the Championship against Lancashire at Liverpool, which Hampshire lost by one run.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He took two hat-tricks (taking three wickets in three balls) during the season, against Gloucestershire and Somerset.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He played for the MCC and the Players during 1920, in addition to appearing for Charles Thornton's personal team at the season-ending Scarborough Festival.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy emerged as a leading all-rounder in 1921, with his batting improving markedly.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He completed the all-rounders double of 1,000 runs and 100 wickets for the first time.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 33 first-class appearances during the season, he took 186 wickets averaging 21.55, taking five or more wickets in an innings on 16 occasions and ten or more in a match four times.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His best innings figures, 8 for 11, came against Glamorgan.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy and Newman led the Hampshire attack in 1921, bowling between them 14,792 deliveries and taking 340 wickets.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Against Sussex at Portsmouth, Kennedy and Newman bowled unchanged throughout the match; such was their dominance that the pair were the top two bowlers in the 1921 County Championship, with Newman taking 172 wickets and Kennedy taking 168.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 1921, he scored 1,305 runs, averaging 26.10; he scored two centuries in July, making scores of 152 not out against Nottinghamshire and 114 against Worcestershire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Achieving consecutive doubles, the 1922 season was to be a record-breaking one for Kennedy.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He took 205 wickets, averaging 16.80 from 34 matches, and taking five or more wickets in an innings on 20 occasions and ten or more in a match on seven.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In the 1922 County Championship, he took 177 wickets, finishing third nationally behind Charlie Parker (195) and Tich Freeman (194); his 190 first-class wickets for Hampshire remain the most wickets taken in a season for the county.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] One of his most notable performances came against Somerset at Bath in the County Championship, when he took match figures of 15 wickets for 116 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In another notable performance, he took figures of 7 for 71 and made a half-century (70 runs) in a 10 run defeat by Sussex at Southampton.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He combined with Newman in Warwickshire's second innings to bowl Hampshire to victory.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Lamenting Hampshire's first innings collapse, Kennedy commented "Every batsman, no matter how good he is, gets a good 'un, some time or other, immediately he gets in - and out he comes.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Well, this happened to all of us in one innings." His 200th wicket came at the season-ending Scarborough Festival, and in taking over 200 wickets and scoring over a thousand runs in the season, he achieved a unique double only matched by George Hirst, Maurice Tate, and Albert Trott.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy's form in 1922 led to him being selected for the MCC's winter tour of South Africa, led by Frank Mann.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He had been due to coach in Cape Town during the winter, but with his selection to the touring party his coaching engagement passed to Newman.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy featured in the five first-class tour matches against South African provincial sides that preceded the Test series, before making his Test debut for England against South Africa at Johannesburg on 23 December.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He played in all five Test's on the tour, ending the series as England's leading wicket-taker with 31 at an average of 19.32.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He was instrumental in England's success during the 5th Test, taking figures of 5 for 76 from nearly 50 overs to help bowl England to victory by 109 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Earlier in the series, he had taken 5 for 88 in the 3rd Test at Durban.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] The cricket journalist Simon Wilde later wrote that his contributions across the series with the ball "were crucial to England's series win".
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Across the entirety of the tour, Kennedy took 61 wickets in the first-class matches played on the tour (inclusive of the Tests), averaging 16.78.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His aggregate placed him three wickets ahead of Percy Fender.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 1923, Kennedy achieved the double for the third consecutive season.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 33 matches, he took 184 wickets at an average of 19.55, claiming five or more wickets in an innings on 18 occasions.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In the County Championship against Somerset, Newman and Kennedy bowled unchanged together for the second time.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He also scored 1,327 runs, including two centuries, and averaged 25.51.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He made the highest score of his first-class career in June against Warwickshire at Portsmouth, scoring an unbeaten 163 runs at the top of the order; the match was notable for Kennedy taking match figures of 9 for 77, which contributed toward Hampshire's victory by 244 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] During the season, he made his only appearance in the North v South match, representing the South without success.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 1924, he took 135 wickets from 32 matches, averaging 20.85.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Amongst the ten five wicket hauls he claimed in 1924, Kennedy took 8 for 24 against Gloucestershire at the beginning of June, taking the third hat-trick of his career in the innings.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] However, his batting form declined, and for the first time in three seasons he did not pass a thousand runs.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Following the conclusion of the season, Kennedy was chosen to tour South Africa with S.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy played in fourteen first-class matches during the tour, against a mixture of provincial sides and the South African national team.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He was the tourists leading wicket-taker with 65 at an average of 19.80.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Returning to England, in the 1925 season, Kennedy took 142 wickets from 33 matches, averaging 18.97 and taking five wickets or more in an innings 11 times.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 1926, he failed to take a hundred wickets in a season for the first time since 1913, with 87 at an average of 31.19 from 30 matches.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] The *Portsmouth Evening News* remarked that he had endured a "lean time", which was attributed to poor health.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He was afforded a benefit against Surrey in 1926, raising £1,095.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His fortunes reversed in 1927, with Kennedy taking 123 wickets at an average of 22.01 from 30 matches and claiming five wickets or more in an innings on ten occasions.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] These figures remained the best-ever in the fixture until its discontinuation in 1962.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] The match was considered the highlight of the English season, with no Test matches having been played that summer.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His batting also recovered in 1927, with Kennedy narrowly missing out on scoring a thousand runs in the season, with 976 at an average of 22.18.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 1928, Kennedy would complete the double for the fourth time in his career.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Across 32 matches, he took 105 wickets, averaging 28.28, and scored 1,437 runs, averaging 26.61, making two centuries.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] The number of wickets he took in 1929 increased, with Kennedy taking 154 at an average of 18 from 29 matches; he took five wickets or more in an innings during the season on 14 occasions, including figures of 9 for 46 at Portsmouth in May to help dismiss Derbyshire for 99 runs.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In 1930, Kennedy would take 120 wickets from 32 matches, averaging of 25.72, and took five or more wickets in an innings on seven occasions.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He would also score 1,006 runs, averaging 20.53; in taking over a hundred wickets and scoring over a thousand runs, he achieved the double for the fifth and final time of his career.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His partnership with Newman, which by 1930 had spanned 20 years, came to an end when Newman retired at the end of the season.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] The following season, Kennedy took 131 wickets, averaging 17.31, and taking five or more wickets in an innings on 11 occasions.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He took 144 wickets in 1932, averaging 18.79, and taking five or more wickets in an innings on 12 occasions; the 1932 season was the final time he would take a hundred wickets in a season.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Following the season, he was chosen as one of five *Wisden* Cricketers of the Year for 1933.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] During the 1933 season, the dry English summer was not conducive to Kennedy's bowling, with him taking 88 wickets at an average of 27.10.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] At the start of the 1934 season, it was announced that Kennedy would be retiring at the end of the season to take up a coaching post at Cheltenham College, having previously coached United Services in Portsmouth.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] During the season, he took 91 wickets, averaging 29.26 — as in 1933, the dry weather that season not being overly conducive to his bowling.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He recorded his final first-class century during the season, with 130 runs against Kent in July.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Following the end of the season, he was afforded a testimonial in 1935 in recognition of the services he had rendered to Hampshire cricket; this raised £397.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Nevertheless, he returned to the Hampshire team in 1935, playing during the school holidays.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Upon his return, he bowled effectively, taking 32 wickets from the seven County Championship matches he played in; in his first match of the season, he took 6 for 94 against Essex, and later took 7 for 46 against Northamptonshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He again played for Hampshire during the school holidays in 1936, making five appearances in which he took 17 wickets.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He retired fully from playing following the conclusion of the 1936 season.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy was a sturdily built man who possessed great stamina.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] A medium-pace bowler, he began with a "beautifully smooth run-up", before delivering the ball with a high arm action and with consistent accuracy.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Such was his accuracy that it was reckoned that he rarely bowled a bad ball.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy possessed the ability to bowl late inswingers, and was also able to impart spin on the ball, turning it from leg.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He was particularly effective with the new ball, a trait that he carried throughout his career with the *Huddersfield Daily Examiner* remarking that even in the formative years of his career, he remained "a very good bowler when the ball is new".
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Hampshire came to rely upon Kennedy's bowling, and following his retirement the *Hampshire Telegraph* reckoned that their bowling had lost much of its effectiveness.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His bowling partnership with Newman was described as "one of the most successful in county cricket".
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Although Kennedy was considered one of the most effective bowlers in county cricket by *Wisden*, he played only five Test matches.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Wilde also thought that his bowling was not of sufficient speed for Test level.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Although he began as a tail-end batsman, Kennedy developed his batting so well that by 1921 he often opened the batting, whilst at Hampshire he was known to have occupied every batting position.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He was described as a "sound batsman" by *Wisden*, while the cricket writer Bill Frindall later described him as a "resolute batsman" who was "sound in defence".
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Although a cautious batter, he occasionally played innings of more aggressive intention.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] When he scored 101 against Kent in 1923, *Wisden* remarked "he was caution itself up to a point, but hit twelve fours".
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] With the development of his batting, Kennedy became one of the most durable and consistent all-rounders in county cricket.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy made 677 appearances in first-class cricket.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He took 2,874 wickets during his career, averaging 21.23, and took five or more wickets in an innings 245 times and ten wickets or more in a match 45 times.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] His career aggregate ranks him seventh on the all-time list of highest wicket-takers in first-class cricket.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] For Hampshire, Kennedy made 596 first-class appearances, second to Mead's 700.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He took 2,549 wickets for Hampshire, averaging 21.16, and took five wickets or more in an innings on 205 occasions and ten wickets or more in a match on 41.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He held the record for the most first-class wickets for Hampshire until 1967, when it was surpassed by Derek Shackleton.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy took 100 wickets in a season on 15 occasions, a record for a Hampshire player until it was also surpassed by Shackleton.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] The similarity in playing styles between Kennedy and Shackleton would later draw comparisons from Arlott.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He completed the double of 1,000 runs and 100 wickets in a season five times between 1921 and 1930; ten doubles have been taken for Hampshire, with Newman and Kennedy accounting for five each.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He had success as a bowler with other first-class teams, beside Hampshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy made 31 appearances for the MCC between 1919 and 1934, taking 120 wickets at 22.84.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He also featured for the Players in the Gentlemen versus Players fixture 17 times between 1914 and 1934, taking 69 wickets at 19.85.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy scored 16,586 runs at an average of 18.53 during his first-class career, making ten centuries and 64 half-centuries.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] For Hampshire, he scored 14,925 runs, with all ten of his centuries made playing for Hampshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He was a capable fielder, taking 531 catches in first-class cricket.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] For Hampshire, he took 484 catches, behind only Peter Sainsbury (601) and Mead (633).
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Following his retirement, Kennedy continued to coach cricket at Cheltenham College, and following the Second World War, he coached in South Africa from 1947 to 1954.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] In later life he ran a tobacconist and stationers shop in Southampton.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy was made an honorary life member at Hampshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] He had been in ill health for several months before his death on 15 November 1959 at the Hythe and Dibden War Memorial Hospital in Hythe, Hampshire.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Kennedy was married with one daughter, with both surviving him.
[src:all-rounder/alec-kennedy] Paying tribute to Kennedy following his death, his teammate and sports journalist Harold Day expressed "There was never a greater hearted trier than Kennedy, nor was there a fairer bowler".
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] Bacher was born in May 1942 in Roodepoort to Lithuanian-Jewish parents who had migrated to South Africa.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He got his nickname "Ali" at the age of seven from the story of Ali Baba.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] Bacher married Shira Teeger in 1965, and they have two daughters and one son.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] His nephew Adam Bacher played Test cricket for South Africa in the 1990s.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He studied at the University of the Witwatersrand and became a general practitioner.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He worked as a GP for nine years but left the field, saying, "I realised I was getting too emotionally involved with the patients." In 1979 he briefly went into a family business.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] Bacher started playing cricket while at King Edward VII School in Johannesburg, and represented Transvaal at the age of 17.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He was appointed captain of Transvaal for the 1963–64 season, in place of John Waite, who was on tour with the South African national side in Australia.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He played in 12 Tests for South Africa, three against England and nine against Australia; he was captain in the last four.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] In a first-class match for Transvaal against the visiting Australian cricket team in 1966–67, he made 235 in the second innings, the record score for any South African team against Australia, took five catches, and led his team to Australia's first ever defeat in South Africa.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He later played important innings in Test victories over Australia in the First, Third and Fifth Tests.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He captained the national team in only one series: in 1969–70 against Australia at home, in which the South Africans won all four Tests.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He was selected to captain the touring teams to England in 1970 and Australia in 1971–72, but neither tour eventuated, owing to anti-apartheid protests in the host countries.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] In 1972 he became the first player to make 5000 runs in the Currie Cup.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He was awarded South Africa's Sports Merit Award (its top athletics honour) in 1972.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] In 1981 Bacher had heart bypass surgery, then took up the job of leading Transvaal's newly professionalised cricket administration.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He was made managing director of the South African Cricket Union in the late 1980s.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] Believing that apartheid would not end in his lifetime, and determined to maintain the vigour of South African cricket, he encouraged tours by "rebel" teams from Sri Lanka, England, West Indies and Australia during the 1980s.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] At the same time he recognised that South African cricket had no long-term future unless cricketers in the non-white communities were encouraged to develop their potential, and he organised mass coaching clinics and development programs in the black townships.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] When apartheid began to collapse in 1990, Bacher immediately set out to form one body to oversee all cricket in South Africa: he contacted Steve Tshwete, the head of the ANC's sports desk, to help get the parties to agree on a unified body.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] Tshwete soon forged an agreement and the two men became friends, travelling to London together in 1991 to successfully apply for South Africa's re-admission to the International Cricket Council.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] Bacher managed the South African team on its brief tour of India in 1991.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] He instigated cricket's first video-review system in 1992 and directed the planning for the 2003 Cricket World Cup.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] In 2005 he joined the board of the South African Rugby Union as the sponsors' representative.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] In 2024, at the South African Jewish Board of Deputies' 120th anniversary gala dinner, he was honoured among 100 remarkable Jewish South Africans who have contributed to South Africa.
[src:all-rounder/ali-bacher] The ceremony included speeches from Chief Rabbi Ephraim Mirvis, and Bacher was honoured among other cricketers such as Norman Gordon, Fred Susskind, Mandy Yachad and Dennis Gamsy.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The **All England Eleven**, widely known as the **AEE**, was an itinerant all-professional cricket team created in 1846 by Nottinghamshire bowler William Clarke.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Widely known by its acronym AEE, it took advantage of opportunities offered by the newly developed railway network to play against local teams throughout Great Britain.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] It made its profit by receiving payments from the home clubs.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The AEE teams were exceptionally strong, and so the local teams would play them in "odds" matches, usually 22 against the AEE's eleven—as such, the majority of AEE games do not have any claim to top-class standard.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] In 1852, some players broke away from the AEE to form the United All England Eleven (UEE).
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Similar enterprises were launched in the following years, including the United North of England Eleven (UNEE), and Ned Willsher's United South of England Eleven (USEE), which became a showcase for W.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Clarke, as well as being the manager, was the captain of the AEE team until his death in 1856.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] He was succeeded by his Nottinghamshire colleague George Parr who agreed that the AEE and UEE should regularly play against each other, something that Clarke would not allow.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Those matches were eleven-a-side and so were important from 1857 to 1863, and first-class from 1864 to the last in 1869.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] In 1859, the first England cricket team was formed as a composite of the AEE and the UEE to tour North America.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] With the rise of county cricket and the introduction of international cricket, the travelling elevens lost influence and popularity.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The AEE gradually faded from the scene, and played its last match 29–30 May 1891 against a local team in Middlesbrough.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] In the late 1840s, Nottinghamshire player William Clarke recognised that a professional touring eleven could enhance the local and fragmented popularity of cricket.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] In 1846, he founded what would become known as the "All England Eleven" as an all-professional team that played "odds matches" in the North of England against local teams.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Clarke originally called his team the "Eleven of England".
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The squad arguably comprised the best English professional players of the time, as well as two nominally "amateur" cricketers, Alfred Mynn and Nicholas Felix.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The team for the first match, which was against Twenty of Sheffield in September 1846, was: Clarke, Mynn, Jemmy Dean, William Dorrinton, Joe Guy, Will Martingell, Tom Sewell Sr, George Butler, Villiers Smith, and William Hillyer.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Commenting on this team, the ACS said that its "quality did justice to its title".
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The All England Eleven was inundated with requests for fixtures.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] It received payment from its opponents, who in turn could hope for a large attendance.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] During the following years, helped by the growth of the railway network, the team regularly toured Great Britain, doing much to increase the popularity of the game in areas that had not previously seen high-class cricket.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] One such match was played from 22 to 24 June 1854 at a venue called Wintle's Field in Bristol, where the AEE met 22 of West Gloucestershire, and won by 149 runs.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The home team included its founders, the brothers-in-law Alfred Pocock and Henry Mills Grace.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Watching the game was Martha Grace, sister of the former and wife of the latter.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] She was with other members of the Grace family, including her five-year-old son W.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] G., who recorded in his *Reminiscences* (1899) that it was the first "great match" he ever saw.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Clarke, who was captain as well as manager of the team, was careful to pay his players more than they could get from Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) or the county clubs (only four had been founded by 1846).
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] However, Clarke kept by far the largest part of the profit for himself.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] In 1852, some of the professionals, led by John Wisden and Jemmy Dean, became dissatisfied with Clarke's ungenerous and undemocratic behaviour.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Seeking increased income, they broke away from the AEE and created the United All England Eleven (UEE).
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Other similar teams appeared from the late 1850s.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] George Parr led the AEE after Clarke's death in 1856.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] From 1857, the two main England Elevens played an annual match against each other.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] In 1859, six members of each team composed the squad of the first-ever English overseas touring team, which played several games in Canada and the United States.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] From 31 August 1846 to 30 May 1891, the AEE played in some 623 matches throughout the country.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Among their venues were College Park, Raeburn Place, and Cardiff Arms Park, in Ireland, Scotland, and Wales respectively.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] In England, they played at several famous cricket grounds, such as Lord's, The Oval, Fenner's, the Hyde Park Ground, North Marine Road, Old Trafford, the Royal Brunswick Ground, and Trent Bridge.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] They also visited places which would become well-known names in football—these included Aston Park, Bramall Lane, Saltergate, Small Heath, Turf Moor, Upton Park, and the Victoria Ground.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The 577 matches in the miscellaneous list were all played against "odds", meaning that the AEE was handicapped by playing against teams of twenty or twenty-two.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Odds matches were common in the 18th and 19th centuries, as a means of handicapping a team acknowledged to have superior strength.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Even in the important/first-class matches, the AEE were often handicapped but by much lesser odds.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] For example, the first match in that list was against Surrey at The Oval in August 1848, and Surrey had fourteen players.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The handicap paid off as Surrey won by 8 wickets, largely thanks to the efforts of Felix, Edmund Hinkly, and Will Martingell who all played for the AEE on other occasions.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The AEE's first eleven-a-side match was in May 1849 when they played the combined Cambridge University and Cambridge Town Club at Fenner's.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] This was a three-day match played as a benefit for F.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Fenner, but it was impacted by bad weather, and ended as a draw.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Only a few eleven-a-side matches were played while Clarke was in charge: three against Kent, two against Surrey, and one each against Sussex and a combined Kent & Sussex team.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Other matches with MCC, Hampshire, and Yorkshire were played against odds of usually 14/11.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The AEE's first defeat in an eleven-a-side match was by Surrey at The Oval in June 1852.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Surrey won by 7 wickets, but a curiosity of this match was that Clarke, Parr, and John Bickley all played for Surrey as given men.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] George Parr assumed leadership of the AEE on Clarke's death in August 1856.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] Parr had no axe to grind with the UEE, and was agreeable to the annual fixture which began at Lord's on 1 June 1857, the AEE winning by 5 wickets.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] The teams met 19 times between then and May 1869.
[src:all-rounder/all-england-eleven] They won eight matches each, and there were three draws.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Vikram Singh (Shakti Kapoor) is the son of a rich businessman.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] He has hired a coach to practice cricket.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] He and his friends play cricket in a ground.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] There Ajay Kumar (Kumar Gaurav), the son of a deceased gardener, is their ballboy.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Ajay is passionate about Cricket and requests Vikram to let him play.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] He tells him that one day he wants to become a cricketer like him.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Vikram chides him saying that poor people should stay in their limits and not dream beyond their means.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Meanwhile, Ajay's brother Birju (Vinod Mehra), a street performer is the sole bread earner of the family.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] One day, Ajay plays wearing Vikram's pads and gloves.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] An angry Vikram thrashes Ajay and throws out his family from their home.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Birju increases his performances with brand collaboration with roadside shops to earn money, so that Ajay can continue his Cricket practice.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] After some years, Vikram is now the Opener of Team India.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] While Ajay is the opener of his University team.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Ajay is a flamboyant stroke player who scores only on the Onside.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Seeing this brilliance, Ritu, the daughter of the Chairman of Selection Committee, falls in live with Ajay.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Vikram wants to marry Ritu but she chooses to be with Ajay.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] After a string of brilliant performances for his university team, Ajay gets directly selected to play for Team India without having ever played a match of Domestic Cricket.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Vikram is dropped from the team for his poor performance and he becomes the 12th Man.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] During the match, Ajay's massive century wins the match for India and he becomes Man of the Match for which he gets a cheque of 21000, a Bungalow, a Government job and what not.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] This angers Vikram who had to serve water to Ajay during the match just like Ajay used to do when they were kids.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] An angry and jealous Vikram sends his girlfriend to Ajay's hotel room.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] The girl manages to coerce Ajay to come to a bar where Ajay gets drunk and compromising photos are clicked of him which get leaked to the print media.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] This leads to Ajay being dropped from the team and being admonished by Ritu.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Birju bashes Ajay and throws him out of his house.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Losing everything overnight, Ajay becomes an alcoholic.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] The girl realizes her mistake and threatens to expose Vikram's petty plan.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Bleeding, she reaches Ajay and with her last dying declaration, confesses that she and Vikram were in the plot.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] Ajay and Birju bash Vikram and get him arrested.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder-1984-film] The movie ends with Ajay becoming a superstar opener for Team India.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] An **all-rounder** is a cricketer who regularly performs well at both batting and bowling.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Although all bowlers must bat and quite a handful of batsmen do bowl occasionally, most players are skilled in only one of the two disciplines and are considered specialists.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Some wicket-keepers have the skills of a specialist batter and have been referred to as all-rounders, but the term *wicket-keeper-batter* is more commonly applied to them, even if they are substitute wicket keepers who also bowl.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] There is no precise qualification for a player to be considered an all-rounder and use of the term tends to be subjective.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] The generally accepted criterion is that a "genuine allrounder" is someone whose batting or bowling skills, considered alone, would be good enough to win them a place in the team.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Another definition of a "genuine all-rounder" is a player who can, through both batting and bowling (though not necessarily both in the same match), consistently "win matches for the team" (i.e., propel their team to victory by an outstanding individual performance).
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] By either definition, a genuine all-rounder is quite rare and extremely valuable to a team, effectively operating as two players.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Confusion sometimes arises when a specialist bowler performs well with the bat.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] For example, West Indies pace bowler Malcolm Marshall achieved ten scores of 50 or above in 107 Test innings between 1978 and 1991, but had a batting average of less than 19.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] He would be termed a "useful lower-order batsman", or indeed "a bowler who bats a bit".
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] One of the main constraints to becoming a recognised all-rounder is that batters and bowlers "peak" at different ages.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Batters tend to reach their peak in their late twenties after their technique has matured through experience.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Conversely, fast bowlers often peak in their early to mid-twenties at the height of their physical prowess.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Other bowlers, mostly spinners but also fast bowlers who can "swing" the ball, are still effective in their later careers.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] In 2013, Ali Bacher used statistical analysis to argue that there had only been 42 genuine all-rounders in the history of Test cricket.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] He rated Garry Sobers as the best, followed by Jacques Kallis.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] One commonly used statistical rule of thumb is that a player's batting average (the higher the better) should be greater than their bowling average (the lower the better).
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] In Test cricket, only two players i.e., Garfield Sobers and Jacques Kallis, have batting averages that are 20 greater than their bowling averages over their entire careers.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] However, some other players have achieved such a differential over significant parts of their careers, such as Imran Khan who across 54 Test matches during the 1980s averaged 44 with the bat and 19 with the ball.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Wally Hammond and Doug Walters managed differences of 20.7 and 19.2, respectively, between their batting and bowling averages, however, they were generally regarded as occasional bowlers who could break partnerships rather than genuine all-rounders.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] In overall first-class cricket, there are several players with significantly higher batting averages.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Statistically, few can challenge Frank Woolley who had a batting average of 40.77 and a bowling average of 19.87.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Woolley took over 2000 wickets in his career, scored more runs than anyone except Jack Hobbs and is the only non-wicketkeeper to have taken more than 1000 catches.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Many all-rounders are better at bowling than batting or *vice versa*.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Very few are equally good at both and hardly any have been outstanding at both.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Thus the terms "bowling all-rounder" and "batting all-rounder" have come into use.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] For example, Richard Hadlee had an excellent bowling average of 22.29 in Tests and a passable (yet unspectacular) batting average of 27.16, leading him to be termed a "bowling all-rounder", while the same can be said about Jason Holder, Kyle Mayers, Justin Greaves and Chris Woakes.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Meanwhile, a player like Jacques Kallis (batting average of 55.37 and bowling average of 32.65 in Tests) is known as a "batting all-rounder".
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Also, batting all-rounders may not bowl much due to injury concerns (e.g.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Corey Anderson, Angelo Mathews), or their batting skills are far better than their bowling to begin with (e.g.
[src:all-rounder/all-rounder] Kane Williamson, Steve Smith) to the point they revert to being known as a batsman.
